<body>
  <p>Hi {{firstName}},</p>

  <p>If {{companyName}} is financing its GPU hardware with debt — equipment finance, private credit, bank lines — you're almost certainly paying more than you need to. Here's why: lenders price GPU-backed loans to account for collateral depreciation risk. That uncertainty gets baked into your rate, your LTV cap, and your covenants.</p>

  <p>Corgi provides Residual Value Guaranty (RVG) insurance for GPU hardware — a put-style floor on your hardware's value at a future date. When your lenders see a guaranteed collateral floor from an insurance carrier, they can offer better rates, longer tenors, and higher LTV ratios. The policy pays for itself in cheaper debt.</p>

  <p>Three things that make this different from everything else you've seen:</p>
  <p>1. <strong>Direct cost-of-capital benefit</strong> — lenders treat RVG-backed GPUs as qualifying collateral with a known floor. Better LTV, longer tenor, tighter spread on your facility.<br>
  2. <strong>Transparent pricing</strong> — we mark policies to SiliconNavigator™ daily benchmarks, not black-box models. Your CFO and your lender can both audit it.<br>
  3. <strong>No moral hazard</strong> — title transfers at settlement. There's no incentive to file a spurious claim because you surrender the hardware to collect.</p>

  <p>We're built for mid-market GPU operators — the $50M to $500M hardware buyer who's debt-financed and wants a cleaner collateral story. If you're equity-funded, RVG still protects your balance sheet from depreciation shock when the next GPU generation lands.</p>

  <p>We've raised $108M and we're actively writing policies on H100 and A100 clusters. Premiums run 2.1% to 12.9% of GPU value depending on guarantee level and term.</p>

  <p>Worth 20 minutes with our founders to walk through how this fits {{companyName}}'s capital structure?</p>

